[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to the scene in the unseen.

00:34:58.440 --> 00:35:03.640
[Amit Varma]: I am talking with Shruti Rajgopalan and she's just finished making a case for why we need

00:35:03.640 --> 00:35:09.120
[Amit Varma]: simple rules for complex problems and our GST is mindlessly complicated instead of being

00:35:09.120 --> 00:35:13.600
[Amit Varma]: the good and simple tax that it was hyped up to be.

00:35:13.600 --> 00:35:17.160
[Amit Varma]: And Shruti, before I continue, and I want to raise a couple of the standard objections

00:35:17.160 --> 00:35:21.560
[Amit Varma]: people make to that, but before that, I just want to try and summarize your position and

00:35:21.560 --> 00:35:23.800
[Amit Varma]: tell me if I missed anything.

00:35:23.800 --> 00:35:28.640
[Amit Varma]: Your position basically is that the complexity of the GST, where you have so many different

00:35:28.640 --> 00:35:34.500
[Amit Varma]: rates for so many different categories, has the impact that compliance costs go up.

00:35:34.500 --> 00:35:39.880
[Amit Varma]: Compliance becomes extremely difficult and a lot of human labor of people in businesses

00:35:39.880 --> 00:35:45.000
[Amit Varma]: and goes into figuring it out, or you hire CAs, which is a cost in itself.

00:35:45.000 --> 00:35:50.000
[Amit Varma]: And what this can do at the margins is that it can drive some businesses out of business

00:35:50.000 --> 00:35:54.720
[Amit Varma]: entirely, and in other cases, it will just raise the cost of those businesses, therefore

00:35:54.720 --> 00:35:59.640
[Amit Varma]: raising the cost for consumers as well, and therefore ending in what seems to be like

00:35:59.640 --> 00:36:03.480
[Amit Varma]: a vicious circle or a negative sum game or whichever way you put it.

00:36:03.480 --> 00:36:09.680
[Amit Varma]: And to stop this negative ripple effect, where everybody suffers except for chartered accountants

00:36:09.680 --> 00:36:15.560
[Amit Varma]: and lawyers, what you propose is that make it a good and simple tax, have one tax rate

00:36:15.560 --> 00:36:21.240
[Amit Varma]: for everything, perhaps for certain goods have no tax rate at all, which are essential

00:36:21.240 --> 00:36:24.640
[Amit Varma]: items for poor people, but otherwise just have one tax rate.

00:36:24.640 --> 00:36:26.240
[Amit Varma]: Have I summed it up correctly?

00:36:26.240 --> 00:36:27.240
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:36:27.240 --> 00:36:31.080
[Guest]: And I just want to add one slightly broader point than the GST.

00:36:31.080 --> 00:36:33.320
[Guest]: We talked a lot about classification, right?

00:36:33.320 --> 00:36:36.820
[Guest]: There are two ways to solve the classification nightmare.

00:36:36.820 --> 00:36:41.560
[Guest]: One is that the government just needs to classify things better, announce it better, and have

00:36:41.560 --> 00:36:44.400
[Guest]: some mechanism by which people get this information quickly.

00:36:44.400 --> 00:36:46.600
[Guest]: So the compliance costs are reduced.

00:36:46.600 --> 00:36:47.920
[Guest]: That is one way of thinking.

00:36:47.920 --> 00:36:51.920
[Guest]: And there is a lot of focus on trying to make the government more efficient at it.

00:36:51.920 --> 00:36:56.200
[Guest]: The other way of thinking is the way you and I have been talking about, which is, let's

00:36:56.200 --> 00:37:02.320
[Guest]: eliminate the need for a complex classification system in the first place, right?

00:37:02.320 --> 00:37:07.720
[Guest]: So if you collapse it to a single rate, everyone needs to pay the same rate, there is no need

00:37:07.720 --> 00:37:11.960
[Guest]: for classification, you kill the complexity automatically, right?

00:37:11.960 --> 00:37:16.120
[Amit Varma]: So now the two sort of objections I want to raise are, to be clear, not my objections,

00:37:16.120 --> 00:37:19.960
[Amit Varma]: I'm entirely on board with you, but these are objections that came up on Twitter, after

00:37:19.960 --> 00:37:23.920
[Amit Varma]: your excellent piece kind of went viral in a small way.

00:37:23.920 --> 00:37:28.420
[Amit Varma]: And I want to give you a chance to address these points that were made.

00:37:28.420 --> 00:37:34.520
[Amit Varma]: One point is that having multiple rates of GST is really not fair or progressive simply

00:37:34.520 --> 00:37:42.360
[Amit Varma]: because to have the same rate for a small kirana store for small goods is not as you

00:37:42.360 --> 00:37:46.160
[Amit Varma]: would for say, a guy who's buying a BMW is not fair.

00:37:46.160 --> 00:37:48.800
[Amit Varma]: Why shouldn't the guy buying the BMW pay more?

00:37:48.800 --> 00:37:53.200
[Guest]: Well, so there are two parts to any kind of tax burden.

00:37:53.200 --> 00:37:58.280
[Guest]: One is actually the tax rate that is levied on the good, right, which is the 5% that you

00:37:58.280 --> 00:38:04.080
[Guest]: have for certain goods in a kirana store versus 28% for luxury items and things like that.

00:38:04.080 --> 00:38:07.720
[Guest]: The second part of the tax burden is the compliance.

00:38:07.720 --> 00:38:14.720
[Guest]: And if you really think about it, the kirana store guy has a greater compliance burden

00:38:14.720 --> 00:38:19.400
[Guest]: when there are lots of classifications versus the guy who's buying the BMW.

00:38:19.400 --> 00:38:23.600
[Guest]: Because he can probably afford a lawyer and a charted accountant, he probably has a few,

00:38:23.600 --> 00:38:24.600
[Guest]: right?

00:38:24.600 --> 00:38:29.280
[Guest]: Same with this BMW showroom, they probably have an army of people helping them manage

00:38:29.280 --> 00:38:34.600
[Guest]: the regulatory and the compliance requirements, whereas the small kirana store guy now has

00:38:34.600 --> 00:38:37.240
[Guest]: this additional burden, right?

00:38:37.240 --> 00:38:42.000
[Guest]: So what people are missing when they talk about progressive tax rates or a fair tax

00:38:42.000 --> 00:38:47.440
[Guest]: rate for people who are using, you know, people of a certain income class who are selling

00:38:47.440 --> 00:38:52.920
[Guest]: or consuming certain products versus people consuming luxury products is the classification

00:38:52.920 --> 00:38:58.320
[Guest]: system imposes an enormous compliance burden, which by the way, doesn't fall equally on

00:38:58.320 --> 00:39:05.560
[Guest]: everyone, it falls at a much greater proportion to the turnover on the little guy, right?

00:39:05.560 --> 00:39:09.280
[Amit Varma]: So the point I'm making is, it's actually the other way around, it's a little guy who

00:39:09.280 --> 00:39:11.280
[Amit Varma]: would benefit from a simple tax.

00:39:11.280 --> 00:39:12.280
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:39:12.280 --> 00:39:16.640
[Guest]: So if you ask people, I mean, there are two demands being made, one that the tax rates

00:39:16.640 --> 00:39:17.640
[Guest]: are too high.

00:39:17.640 --> 00:39:23.080
[Guest]: And the second that it's too complex, virtually everyone is on board with simplifying the

00:39:23.080 --> 00:39:27.760
[Guest]: tax system, including the little guy, then you can talk about, you know, when you have

00:39:27.760 --> 00:39:32.040
[Guest]: a single rate, I think it's very important to have a debate about what that single rate

00:39:32.040 --> 00:39:33.040
[Guest]: should be.

00:39:33.040 --> 00:39:34.040
[Guest]: Right.

00:39:34.040 --> 00:39:35.720
[Guest]: And I think the lower the better.

00:39:35.720 --> 00:39:42.400
[Guest]: So Singapore has a 7% GST, Australia has a 10% GST, we have some of the highest GST rates

00:39:42.400 --> 00:39:43.400
[Guest]: in the world.

00:39:43.400 --> 00:39:48.080
[Guest]: So ours need not be seven or 10%, right, we need, we need revenues to come in.

00:39:48.080 --> 00:39:52.240
[Guest]: So there is an argument to be made there that maybe that single rate can be a little bit

00:39:52.240 --> 00:39:56.680
[Guest]: higher, it's not in single digits, maybe it's in the low to mid teens.

00:39:56.680 --> 00:40:02.320
[Guest]: But this, this argument that you know, the kirana guy is being treated unfairly because

00:40:02.320 --> 00:40:07.240
[Guest]: by collapsing to a single rate, my answer is just the kirana guy is being treated unfairly

00:40:07.240 --> 00:40:11.700
[Guest]: when you have multiplication of classification and complexity in rates also.

00:40:11.700 --> 00:40:13.040
[Guest]: So I don't think you're helping that.

00:40:13.040 --> 00:40:14.040
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:40:14.040 --> 00:40:17.600
[Amit Varma]: I mean, the compliance costs are hitting the poor, the much more and therefore you want

00:40:17.600 --> 00:40:21.440
[Amit Varma]: to reduce the compliance costs and what the single rate should be is not an argument you're

00:40:21.440 --> 00:40:22.440
[Amit Varma]: making right now.

00:40:22.440 --> 00:40:25.080
[Amit Varma]: You're just saying that there should be a single rate.

00:40:25.080 --> 00:40:26.080
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:40:26.080 --> 00:40:29.620
[Guest]: So, you know, there are many ways to figure out what that single rate should be depending

00:40:29.620 --> 00:40:31.200
[Guest]: on the end goal.

00:40:31.200 --> 00:40:35.840
[Guest]: You know, you can have good projections for what that single rate will get you in terms

00:40:35.840 --> 00:40:37.200
[Guest]: of revenue.

00:40:37.200 --> 00:40:42.240
[Guest]: So think about this, if people stop spending money on chartered accountants and lawyers

00:40:42.240 --> 00:40:48.360
[Guest]: and approaching the GST council and tax tribunals, right, that money can either go towards business

00:40:48.360 --> 00:40:50.640
[Guest]: or it can go towards the higher tax rate.

00:40:50.640 --> 00:40:51.640
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:40:51.640 --> 00:40:52.640
[Guest]: Right.

00:40:52.640 --> 00:40:53.640
[Guest]: A penny saved is a penny earned.

00:40:53.640 --> 00:40:58.280
[Guest]: So if you save money on compliance, you can raise it either as revenue or it can go back

00:40:58.280 --> 00:41:00.400
[Guest]: in the economy through productive businesses.

00:41:00.400 --> 00:41:01.400
[Amit Varma]: Right.

00:41:01.400 --> 00:41:04.760
[Amit Varma]: And the government therefore makes the same amount of money, if not more, either by the

00:41:04.760 --> 00:41:10.000
[Amit Varma]: money saved on compliance coming back as higher taxes or preferably going back into the economy

00:41:10.000 --> 00:41:13.720
[Amit Varma]: and just increasing the tax base and there being more business to begin with.

00:41:13.720 --> 00:41:14.720
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:41:14.720 --> 00:41:17.760
[Guest]: And I think there is a very important argument to be made that I didn't make this argument

00:41:17.760 --> 00:41:22.320
[Guest]: in the column, but right now a number of items are excluded from GST.

00:41:22.320 --> 00:41:23.320
[Guest]: Right.

00:41:23.320 --> 00:41:26.560
[Guest]: The most important being real estate and alcohol.

00:41:26.560 --> 00:41:34.000
[Guest]: So I think it's very, very important to broaden the GST base and include all goods and services.

00:41:34.000 --> 00:41:35.000
[Guest]: Right.

00:41:35.000 --> 00:41:40.880
[Guest]: That is going to result in a much higher, much better tax collection, as well as a much

00:41:40.880 --> 00:41:47.640
[Guest]: simpler and fairer tax system across the board for everyone, minimizing all this kind of

00:41:47.640 --> 00:41:51.640
[Guest]: regulatory arbitrage that people engage in when it comes to real estate and things like

00:41:51.640 --> 00:41:52.640
[Guest]: that.

00:41:52.640 --> 00:41:59.080
[Guest]: And I think a better argument to make when it comes to raising revenue and being fair,

00:41:59.080 --> 00:42:05.920
[Guest]: you know, to the poorer groups in the economy is that you need to expand the tax base, not

00:42:05.920 --> 00:42:08.800
[Guest]: necessarily have multiple tax systems.

00:42:08.800 --> 00:42:09.800
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

00:42:09.800 --> 00:42:16.120
[Amit Varma]: Let's, let's move on now to the second objection, which is the objection of revenue neutrality,

00:42:16.120 --> 00:42:19.520
[Amit Varma]: which basically, let me try to first sum up what the objection is, and you can tell me

00:42:19.520 --> 00:42:23.600
[Amit Varma]: if I've summed it up correctly, and then you can continue addressing it.

00:42:23.600 --> 00:42:27.600
[Amit Varma]: Revenue neutrality basically means is that look, we move from one system to another system

00:42:27.600 --> 00:42:32.240
[Amit Varma]: from hazard different taxes across states and so on to one GST with all these rates

00:42:32.240 --> 00:42:35.020
[Amit Varma]: and exemptions, which applies to the whole country.

00:42:35.020 --> 00:42:39.880
[Amit Varma]: And at one level, revenue neutrality states that you achieve revenue neutrality when you

00:42:39.880 --> 00:42:44.720
[Amit Varma]: get in as much money in this new system, that is the government takes in as much money in

00:42:44.720 --> 00:42:48.160
[Amit Varma]: this new system as they were getting before GST.

00:42:48.160 --> 00:42:53.000
[Amit Varma]: And at another level, when you talk of revenue neutrality, it is a guarantee given by governments

00:42:53.000 --> 00:42:57.880
[Amit Varma]: to states that the amount of revenue you guys make under GST that goes to you will be the

00:42:57.880 --> 00:43:02.720
[Amit Varma]: same as you were making before GST, which is a guarantee they had to give to get the

00:43:02.720 --> 00:43:06.480
[Amit Varma]: states to agree to GST in the first place.

00:43:06.480 --> 00:43:10.440
[Amit Varma]: And the objection that therefore people are raising is that if you have just one rate

00:43:10.440 --> 00:43:15.240
[Amit Varma]: for everything, instead of these different rates, won't that affect revenue neutrality?

00:43:15.240 --> 00:43:16.560
[Guest]: Have I summed that up correctly?

00:43:16.560 --> 00:43:18.760
[Guest]: Absolutely, I couldn't have said it better.

00:43:18.760 --> 00:43:23.280
[Guest]: So Amit, you're absolutely right, there is a huge question of revenue neutrality.

00:43:23.280 --> 00:43:27.480
[Guest]: This has been something that's been looming large at the macro level since the inception

00:43:27.480 --> 00:43:28.480
[Guest]: of GST, right?

00:43:28.480 --> 00:43:34.200
[Guest]: Like until you implement a new tax system, you don't know how much revenue it's going

00:43:34.200 --> 00:43:35.200
[Guest]: to generate.

00:43:35.200 --> 00:43:42.080
[Guest]: And there was a really big fear that the already depleting coffers of many of the Indian states

00:43:42.080 --> 00:43:45.920
[Guest]: will deplete further because they agreed to this unified tax system.

00:43:45.920 --> 00:43:48.960
[Guest]: Now there is some good news on that end, right?

00:43:48.960 --> 00:43:55.520
[Guest]: So Arvind Subramaniam, our current economic advisor, our current outgoing economic advisor,

00:43:55.520 --> 00:43:59.480
[Guest]: just recently wrote a piece based on nine months of revenue collections.

00:43:59.480 --> 00:44:02.200
[Guest]: So until April this year, right?

00:44:02.200 --> 00:44:06.840
[Guest]: On how in the first nine months, some months you've had, you know, a decrease in revenue

00:44:06.840 --> 00:44:11.040
[Guest]: collections versus the same time last year, some months there has been an increase.

00:44:11.040 --> 00:44:17.240
[Guest]: But overall for the nine months, there has actually been an increase in revenue collections,

00:44:17.240 --> 00:44:18.560
[Guest]: right?

00:44:18.560 --> 00:44:22.360
[Guest]: So this is something that is quite remarkable and something unexpected.

00:44:22.360 --> 00:44:28.600
[Guest]: So there is actually a revenue growth of 11.9% compared to the pre-GST numbers.

00:44:28.600 --> 00:44:34.560
[Guest]: And this basically means he's made a great argument that there is a tax buoyancy of 1.2.

00:44:34.560 --> 00:44:40.040
[Guest]: So tax buoyancy is the responsiveness of tax growth to nominal GDP growth.

00:44:40.040 --> 00:44:43.340
[Guest]: So as the GDP grows, how much does your tax revenue grow?

00:44:43.340 --> 00:44:47.240
[Guest]: So that number is called tax buoyancy, that's 1.2%.

00:44:47.240 --> 00:44:50.680
[Guest]: So the chief economic advisor has actually given us some good news.

00:44:50.680 --> 00:44:57.280
[Guest]: Like we can really breathe a little more comfortably now that we are not just revenue neutral in

00:44:57.280 --> 00:44:59.280
[Guest]: the first nine months, actually revenue plus.

00:44:59.280 --> 00:45:01.240
[Guest]: So that's one aspect, right?

00:45:01.240 --> 00:45:06.520
[Guest]: So in that sense, the GST has been a success in that, you know, our revenue collection

00:45:06.520 --> 00:45:10.840
[Guest]: system didn't just completely collapse when we shifted from system one to system two.

00:45:10.840 --> 00:45:16.280
[Guest]: The second part of revenue collection is most of the states are not doing as badly.

00:45:16.280 --> 00:45:20.960
[Guest]: The ones that were expected to do badly are not doing as badly in revenue collection as

00:45:20.960 --> 00:45:23.020
[Guest]: was originally anticipated.

00:45:23.020 --> 00:45:27.880
[Guest]: So Arvind Subramaniam says that the payout that the central government will have to make

00:45:27.880 --> 00:45:33.600
[Guest]: to the states is much smaller than what was feared or anticipated before.

00:45:33.600 --> 00:45:40.000
[Guest]: So in one sense, even the current extremely complex system we have seen is revenue neutral.

00:45:40.000 --> 00:45:46.560
[Guest]: Now coming to the original question that you asked, revenue neutrality is not determined

00:45:46.560 --> 00:45:49.080
[Guest]: by how many different rates you have.

00:45:49.080 --> 00:45:51.920
[Guest]: It is determined by what is the revenue collection.

00:45:51.920 --> 00:45:57.240
[Guest]: So you can have revenue neutral, revenue plus or revenue minus, depending on what the rate

00:45:57.240 --> 00:45:58.240
[Guest]: is.

00:45:58.240 --> 00:46:04.240
[Guest]: So let's say the single tax rate is 2%, right, and it's levied on everything.

00:46:04.240 --> 00:46:07.920
[Guest]: It's possible that at such a low tax rate, you are not revenue neutral, you're revenue

00:46:07.920 --> 00:46:09.480
[Guest]: minus, right?

00:46:09.480 --> 00:46:12.800
[Guest]: But let's say the single tax rate is 18%.

00:46:12.800 --> 00:46:17.680
[Guest]: It is wholly possible that even under that single rate, you are revenue plus as opposed

00:46:17.680 --> 00:46:19.040
[Guest]: to being revenue neutral.

00:46:19.040 --> 00:46:25.120
[Guest]: So the idea of revenue neutrality is the total of how much revenue you collect.

00:46:25.120 --> 00:46:27.560
[Guest]: Now that is obviously determined by your tax rate, right?

00:46:27.560 --> 00:46:32.280
[Guest]: There is something in economics, there's a Laffer curve, right, as tax rates increase,

00:46:32.280 --> 00:46:34.960
[Guest]: first the revenue collection goes up, then it goes down.

00:46:34.960 --> 00:46:38.880
[Guest]: So you want to figure out where India is on this curve.

00:46:38.880 --> 00:46:42.240
[Guest]: With some goods, you're going to win some, with some goods, you're going to lose some.

00:46:42.240 --> 00:46:47.200
[Guest]: So you know, there are some goods like say tobacco, which are highly non-responsive to

00:46:47.200 --> 00:46:49.500
[Guest]: increases in tax, right?

00:46:49.500 --> 00:46:53.680
[Guest]: So in those cases, a high tax rate will actually get you more revenue.

00:46:53.680 --> 00:46:58.120
[Guest]: Some things like onions, you're going to lose if you impose a very high rate on it, the

00:46:58.120 --> 00:46:59.840
[Guest]: revenue is actually going to go down.

00:46:59.840 --> 00:47:03.840
[Guest]: So you're going to win some, you're going to lose some with a single tax rate.

00:47:03.840 --> 00:47:09.400
[Guest]: But on the whole, it is wholly possible that if you have one single rate, and you find

00:47:09.400 --> 00:47:13.880
[Guest]: the correct rate, you are not just revenue neutral, but you are revenue plus.

00:47:13.880 --> 00:47:18.640
[Amit Varma]: So to sum it up, your point is that as far as revenue neutrality is concerned, it won't

00:47:18.640 --> 00:47:23.260
[Amit Varma]: be affected necessarily by merely simplifying the GST and having one tax.

00:47:23.260 --> 00:47:26.280
[Amit Varma]: What will affect is what that one tax is.

00:47:26.280 --> 00:47:29.160
[Amit Varma]: And that is a separate argument that you're not getting into now.

00:47:29.160 --> 00:47:32.920
[Amit Varma]: You're not saying whether one tax should be 18 or two, you're just saying we should have

00:47:32.920 --> 00:47:35.360
[Amit Varma]: one tax and remove those compliance costs.

00:47:35.360 --> 00:47:38.120
[Amit Varma]: And then let us talk about what that one number should be.

00:47:38.120 --> 00:47:42.840
[Amit Varma]: And we can fix it at something that gives us confidence that revenue neutrality at least

00:47:42.840 --> 00:47:43.840
[Guest]: will be achieved.

00:47:43.840 --> 00:47:47.800
[Guest]: And you know, if you think about it, you know, all of us can appreciate that the government

00:47:47.800 --> 00:47:51.920
[Guest]: is trying to do something quite extraordinary in terms of scale, right?

00:47:51.920 --> 00:47:54.680
[Guest]: So there's going to be some trial and error in the system.

00:47:54.680 --> 00:47:56.480
[Guest]: I think we all can agree to that.

00:47:56.480 --> 00:48:00.640
[Guest]: So it is possible that you start with the rate and like Goldilocks, you need to move

00:48:00.640 --> 00:48:02.280
[Guest]: higher or lower.

00:48:02.280 --> 00:48:03.280
[Guest]: And that's okay.

00:48:03.280 --> 00:48:05.160
[Guest]: I don't think that's a very big problem.

00:48:05.160 --> 00:48:10.360
[Guest]: But remember, that is going to be a trial and error with only one rate, which minimizes

00:48:10.360 --> 00:48:11.360
[Guest]: confusion.

00:48:11.360 --> 00:48:15.080
[Guest]: You know, you open the first page of the newspaper, it says GST Council has increased the rate

00:48:15.080 --> 00:48:16.080
[Guest]: or decreased the rate.

00:48:16.080 --> 00:48:17.080
[Amit Varma]: And that's all you need to know.

00:48:17.080 --> 00:48:18.080
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

00:48:18.080 --> 00:48:19.080
[Guest]: Right.

00:48:19.080 --> 00:48:23.560
[Guest]: So that trial and error process, if we concede that that's going to happen, it'll be simpler.

00:48:23.560 --> 00:48:28.880
[Guest]: The other part of it is, a lot of the revenue neutrality arguments are also dependent on

00:48:28.880 --> 00:48:29.880
[Guest]: the tax base.

00:48:29.880 --> 00:48:35.200
[Guest]: And we don't see enough writing on that in the current GST framework, that we actually

00:48:35.200 --> 00:48:40.360
[Guest]: need to expand the base, we need to cover everything, we need to stop exempting things

00:48:40.360 --> 00:48:44.320
[Guest]: like gold and gemstones at ridiculously low rates, right?

00:48:44.320 --> 00:48:49.520
[Guest]: Gold is taxed at 3%, gemstones, diamonds are taxed at 0.25%.

00:48:49.520 --> 00:48:52.280
[Guest]: So we're making, you know, all this crazy exemptions.

00:48:52.280 --> 00:48:57.720
[Guest]: So there's a really important question of eliminating all these exemptions and increasing

00:48:57.720 --> 00:49:06.760
[Guest]: the tax base to things like alcohol and property taxes, and then simplifying down to one tax

00:49:06.760 --> 00:49:07.760
[Guest]: rate.

00:49:07.760 --> 00:49:11.360
[Guest]: And I don't think there is a very big problem of revenue neutrality.

00:49:11.360 --> 00:49:16.320
[Guest]: I think long run, India will generate more revenue under a system like that.

00:49:16.320 --> 00:49:20.200
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, just to go back to public choice, which we mentioned at the start of this episode,

00:49:20.200 --> 00:49:24.440
[Amit Varma]: what typically happens when you have so many exemptions and so much discretion to people

00:49:24.440 --> 00:49:29.240
[Amit Varma]: in authority is that you will have all these interest groups coming up and there is scope

00:49:29.240 --> 00:49:32.100
[Amit Varma]: for corruption, which is almost inevitable, I would say.

00:49:32.100 --> 00:49:35.240
[Amit Varma]: And you will have your gemstone lobby and your alcohol lobby and all these different

00:49:35.240 --> 00:49:36.240
[Amit Varma]: lobbyings.

00:49:36.240 --> 00:49:39.760
[Amit Varma]: And then it just becomes that same old interplay between power and money.

00:49:39.760 --> 00:49:40.760
[Guest]: Absolutely.

00:49:40.760 --> 00:49:47.240
[Guest]: I think you and I could come up with very good ideas on why we have so many exemptions,

00:49:47.240 --> 00:49:49.640
[Guest]: knowing all the public choice literature that we know.

00:49:49.640 --> 00:49:56.040
[Guest]: I think another question is, how do we persuade all these different groups to come under one

00:49:56.040 --> 00:49:57.040
[Guest]: umbrella?

00:49:57.040 --> 00:49:58.040
[Guest]: Right.

00:49:58.040 --> 00:50:03.040
[Guest]: And I think we are very well poised in this moment, you know, normally for someone like

00:50:03.040 --> 00:50:08.360
[Guest]: you and me, who are strong believers in federalism, it's quite frightening to have single party

00:50:08.360 --> 00:50:10.560
[Guest]: rule in so many states, right?

00:50:10.560 --> 00:50:13.760
[Guest]: Just from a point of view of concentration of power, it doesn't matter which party it

00:50:13.760 --> 00:50:14.760
[Amit Varma]: is.

00:50:14.760 --> 00:50:15.760
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

00:50:15.760 --> 00:50:17.840
[Guest]: Especially given that we have a fairly weak constitution in some ways.

00:50:17.840 --> 00:50:18.840
[Guest]: Exactly.

00:50:18.840 --> 00:50:23.560
[Guest]: And so right now, we are in a very interesting moment, which has happened, you know, after

00:50:23.560 --> 00:50:30.600
[Guest]: the great Nehruvian times, which is 21 states are under one party rule.

00:50:30.600 --> 00:50:37.860
[Guest]: So there is some case to be made that if there is anyone who can unify all these different

00:50:37.860 --> 00:50:42.800
[Guest]: interests and bring them under one umbrella and persuade them, it is the current ruling

00:50:42.800 --> 00:50:44.400
[Guest]: party and the current Prime Minister.

00:50:44.400 --> 00:50:47.040
[Guest]: I don't think that would be an unfair thing to say.

00:50:47.040 --> 00:50:51.480
[Guest]: So we are in a good, I mean, there are many bad things that come from concentration of

00:50:51.480 --> 00:50:52.480
[Guest]: power.

00:50:52.480 --> 00:50:57.920
[Guest]: But it also provides an opportunity to overcome all this kind of interest group activity and

00:50:57.920 --> 00:50:58.920
[Guest]: capture.

00:50:58.920 --> 00:51:04.200
[Guest]: So I would really, I would hope that the current government capitalizes on that moment and

00:51:04.200 --> 00:51:06.540
[Guest]: actually does that for the GST.

00:51:06.540 --> 00:51:10.520
[Amit Varma]: So I'm actually for the rest of this episode, I'm going to ask you only questions related

00:51:10.520 --> 00:51:14.660
[Amit Varma]: to public choice theory, because I want to explore the sort of political economy of why

00:51:14.660 --> 00:51:18.760
[Amit Varma]: the GST is what it is and how it can be reformed.

00:51:18.760 --> 00:51:24.400
[Amit Varma]: What are the sort of incentives in play which could prompt people in power to make that

00:51:24.400 --> 00:51:26.340
[Amit Varma]: move towards a single tax rate?

00:51:26.340 --> 00:51:31.780
[Amit Varma]: And what are the kind of incentives in play which could make those in power resist such

00:51:31.780 --> 00:51:32.780
[Guest]: a move?

00:51:32.780 --> 00:51:38.700
[Guest]: So I'll give you a couple of examples right now, I think there is a very unified lobby,

00:51:38.700 --> 00:51:43.140
[Guest]: you know, even if we break down the different goods and services in the economy to different

00:51:43.140 --> 00:51:49.260
[Guest]: lobbies, I think they're all asking for exemptions and special privileges and things like that.

00:51:49.260 --> 00:51:54.220
[Guest]: But I think there is a lot of unity in that everyone wants this to be a simpler system.

00:51:54.220 --> 00:51:55.220
[Amit Varma]: No question.

00:51:55.220 --> 00:51:56.220
[Amit Varma]: Right?

00:51:56.220 --> 00:52:00.500
[Amit Varma]: Because once everybody can benefit, like normally what happens is that the benefits are concentrated

00:52:00.500 --> 00:52:03.360
[Guest]: and the costs are dispersed.

00:52:03.360 --> 00:52:08.120
[Guest]: So in terms of compliance and complexity, I think there is a lot of unity virtually

00:52:08.120 --> 00:52:14.140
[Guest]: every industry lobby that has been coming to both the GST Council and the government

00:52:14.140 --> 00:52:17.460
[Guest]: have been persuading the government to create a simpler system.

00:52:17.460 --> 00:52:22.540
[Guest]: And both Mr. Jaitley, and you know, the current economic advisor, Mr. Subramanian, they have

00:52:22.540 --> 00:52:28.580
[Guest]: all talked about how there is going to be some discussion and move towards simplifying

00:52:28.580 --> 00:52:34.740
[Guest]: the current GST tax rate system, right, so collapse it down to fewer rates, eliminate

00:52:34.740 --> 00:52:35.740
[Guest]: some of the exemptions.

00:52:35.740 --> 00:52:41.220
[Guest]: So I think this is very much on everyone's mind, because all the industry lobbies have

00:52:41.220 --> 00:52:42.540
[Guest]: been talking about this.

00:52:42.540 --> 00:52:43.740
[Guest]: What could mitigate that?

00:52:43.740 --> 00:52:44.740
[Guest]: Yeah.

00:52:44.740 --> 00:52:48.260
[Guest]: So what can mitigate that is some lobbies actually become strong, like we've seen a

00:52:48.260 --> 00:52:53.460
[Guest]: very strong Gujarat lobby that has ended up with ridiculously low rates for gold and gemstones,

00:52:53.460 --> 00:52:54.460
[Guest]: right?

00:52:54.460 --> 00:52:59.620
[Guest]: Somebody says, okay, don't give us a simple rate, just give us a special rate.

00:52:59.620 --> 00:53:00.820
[Guest]: Right?

00:53:00.820 --> 00:53:05.740
[Guest]: It's going to be too difficult to unify everyone and bring it under one tax rate and compliance

00:53:05.740 --> 00:53:06.740
[Guest]: umbrella.

00:53:06.740 --> 00:53:10.020
[Guest]: Hume thoda special treatment de do, hum aapke khas hain.

00:53:10.020 --> 00:53:11.260
[Guest]: That is sort of the attitude.

00:53:11.260 --> 00:53:13.220
[Guest]: And we have seen that happening.

00:53:13.220 --> 00:53:14.220
[Guest]: Right?

00:53:14.220 --> 00:53:21.060
[Guest]: Basically, industries which don't have much power or much lobbying capacity at the state

00:53:21.060 --> 00:53:26.540
[Guest]: and federal level, especially entertainment, right, different states put all kinds of stresses

00:53:26.540 --> 00:53:27.900
[Guest]: on entertainment.

00:53:27.900 --> 00:53:32.140
[Guest]: It's very difficult for them to lobby or like spend money on lobbying instead of spending

00:53:32.140 --> 00:53:35.460
[Guest]: money on making movies or making music.

00:53:35.460 --> 00:53:40.140
[Guest]: On the other hand, tobacco, alcohol, you know, some of these lobbies are just very well organized.

00:53:40.140 --> 00:53:44.100
[Guest]: So they will be very good at getting their special rates, right?

00:53:44.100 --> 00:53:49.300
[Guest]: And to neutralize the effect of the special rates, some goods which are used by everyone,

00:53:49.300 --> 00:53:53.620
[Guest]: which are not well organized, are going to have this cess and that cess in addition to

00:53:53.620 --> 00:53:55.820
[Guest]: the highest 28% GST.

00:53:55.820 --> 00:54:02.380
[Guest]: So this is, this is a problem of special interests, and in the short run, special interest trying

00:54:02.380 --> 00:54:06.960
[Guest]: to capture whatever gains there are, when there is a lot of confusion and transition

00:54:06.960 --> 00:54:08.340
[Guest]: in a new tax system.

00:54:08.340 --> 00:54:12.100
[Amit Varma]: And what is your sense of which side is stronger?

00:54:12.100 --> 00:54:16.980
[Amit Varma]: You know, is it likely that we will simplify to the extent you want or because typically

00:54:16.980 --> 00:54:21.740
[Amit Varma]: what happens in government is that regulation only gets deeper and more complex because

00:54:21.740 --> 00:54:25.460
[Amit Varma]: of all the interest groups and the incentives involved, it rarely gets simpler.

00:54:25.460 --> 00:54:29.220
[Guest]: But you know, there is a huge incentive in this case, right?

00:54:29.220 --> 00:54:35.380
[Guest]: If things get more complex, and we go back to our good old system of Parchi, you know,

00:54:35.380 --> 00:54:40.180
[Guest]: there is a bit so you can't put India doesn't have the state capacity to throw everyone

00:54:40.180 --> 00:54:43.000
[Guest]: in jail if they evade tax, right?

00:54:43.000 --> 00:54:47.420
[Guest]: If you have a highly complex system and very high tax rates, what's going to happen, people

00:54:47.420 --> 00:54:49.500
[Guest]: will just stop paying.

00:54:49.500 --> 00:54:50.500
[Guest]: Then it's more beneficial.

00:54:50.500 --> 00:54:55.180
[Guest]: You know, I recently last time I was in India, I went with my mom to our tailor.

00:54:55.180 --> 00:54:57.540
[Guest]: She has two sets of books.

00:54:57.540 --> 00:54:59.020
[Guest]: One is GST compliant.

00:54:59.020 --> 00:55:02.080
[Guest]: The other one is all Parchi, start to finish Parchi.

00:55:02.080 --> 00:55:07.640
[Guest]: So all her inputs, people give a Parchi and then she gives us a Parchi, right?

00:55:07.640 --> 00:55:12.860
[Guest]: So what is going to happen is if the compliance requirements are too high, or if the tax rates

00:55:12.860 --> 00:55:18.060
[Guest]: are too high, people will just start evading and when people evade tax, no matter how beautiful

00:55:18.060 --> 00:55:21.500
[Guest]: your GST system is, the government doesn't have revenue.

00:55:21.500 --> 00:55:26.940
[Guest]: So I think one major fear for the current government and any future government is we

00:55:26.940 --> 00:55:32.620
[Guest]: can't mess up the system so much that there is a genuine loss in revenue.

00:55:32.620 --> 00:55:37.540
[Guest]: I think there is some push towards simplifying the system to increase revenue.

00:55:37.540 --> 00:55:42.620
[Guest]: And remember, the more revenue you have, the greater power you have as a ruling party.

00:55:42.620 --> 00:55:47.820
[Amit Varma]: So out of sheer self interest, the evil force will be prompted to do a good thing.

00:55:47.820 --> 00:55:49.900
[Amit Varma]: Or not do a terribly bad thing.

00:55:49.900 --> 00:55:52.300
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I was I was being tongue in cheek there.

00:55:52.300 --> 00:55:55.320
[Amit Varma]: And I'm going to twist your words out of context, because it gives me pleasure.

00:55:55.320 --> 00:55:59.820
[Amit Varma]: What Shruti has just called for is civil disobedience on a mass scale.

00:55:59.820 --> 00:56:03.220
[Amit Varma]: Don't pay your taxes until the GST gets reformed.

00:56:03.220 --> 00:56:07.900
[Amit Varma]: I won't even ask you if that's a fair summary or not, because it obviously is.

00:56:07.900 --> 00:56:09.900
[Guest]: And on that happy note, Shruti, thanks so much.

00:56:09.900 --> 00:56:15.340
[Guest]: I think, no, it's not a fair summary, but I will say I think all forms of protest are

00:56:15.340 --> 00:56:16.340
[Amit Varma]: legitimate.

00:56:16.340 --> 00:56:17.340
[Guest]: I was kidding.

00:56:17.340 --> 00:56:18.340
[Guest]: Right.

00:56:18.340 --> 00:56:24.300
[Guest]: No, but I think people can protest by saying we refuse to file, do what it is you wish,

00:56:24.300 --> 00:56:26.260
[Guest]: because your system's really terrible.

00:56:26.260 --> 00:56:32.940
[Guest]: We have fantastic history in India of objecting to unfair taxes, starting with the salt tax.

00:56:32.940 --> 00:56:33.940
[Amit Varma]: Exactly.

00:56:33.940 --> 00:56:35.460
[Guest]: That is a civil disobedience movement.

00:56:35.460 --> 00:56:42.620
[Guest]: So I can very much get behind kirana shops who say this is just too complicated.

00:56:42.620 --> 00:56:44.300
[Guest]: You have got to simplify this.

00:56:44.300 --> 00:56:47.620
[Guest]: Otherwise, by all means, you know, shut our shops and throw us in jail.

00:56:47.620 --> 00:56:50.660
[Guest]: I think, in fact, I would in fact call for that.

00:56:50.660 --> 00:56:53.060
[Amit Varma]: I would love if we could organize like that.

00:56:53.060 --> 00:56:58.540
